#Text=Cypriot plane with 121 on board crashes in Greece
#Text=Sunday , August 14 , 2005

#Text=A Helios airliner ( Boeing 737 , flight HCY 522 ) with 115 passengers and 6 crew onboard has crashed into a mountain at 09:04 UTC ( 12:04 p.m. EEST ) near Grammatiko , 40 kilometres ( 25 miles ) north of Athens , while approaching the capital 's airport .
#Text=All on board perished .
#Text=The plane was travelling from Larnaca , in the southeast of Cyprus ( Greek : Kypros , Κύπρος ) and scheduled to arrive in Prague after a stop in Athens .
#Text=In-flight events
#Text=Immediately after take-off , the pilots reported a problem with the air conditioning system of the aircraft and requested to stay at a low altitude .
#Text=A few minutes later , the pilots alerted the station that the problem had been fixed and requested permission to ascend .
#Text=This information however has been denied by the Director of Helios Airways .
#Text=As the plane approached Athens , all communication abruptly ceased , and the plane never issued a mayday distress signal .
#Text=Two Greek F-16 military aircraft were assigned to observe the plane .
#Text=The pilots of the F-16s noted that one airliner pilot appeared to be unconscious and the other was not in the cockpit .
#Text=CBC reported the following :

#Text=On Wednesday [ August 17 , 2005 ] , state-run and private media , quoting anonymous defense ministry officials , said the two fighter pilots saw someone in the cockpit take control of the plane , which was flying in a gradually descending holding pattern apparently on autopilot .

#Text=That person , probably a man who experts say must have had flight training , then banked the plane away from Athens , lowering it to 2,000 feet and then climbing back up to 7,000 feet before the plane apparently ran out of fuel and crashed .
#Text=The F-16s accompanied the airliner until it crashed .
#Text=Possible malfunctions and causes
#Text=The Greek F-16 pilots saw at least one of the aircraft 's pilots may have become unconscious before the crash , causing control of the plane to be lost .
#Text=The emergency oxygen masks were also reported to have dropped .
#Text=There had been speculation that an electrical fire or some other cause could have flooded the cabin with carbon monoxide or another gas that would render the passengers unconscious .
#Text=However , the chief coroner of Athens , Greece , said that tests showed none of the passengers or crew had carbon monoxide in their blood .
#Text=It was also speculated that the air-supply system of the aircraft may have failed , causing a loss of air pressure within the cockpit .
#Text=This malfunction can cause a steep drop in air temperature .
#Text=On December 16 , 2004 the same aircraft made an emergency landing after failure of the ventilation system at 35,000 feet and 3 passengers were hospitalized .
#Text=However , an airline spokesman insisted that the plane was airworthy when it took off .
#Text=Tests showed that at least 26 people on the flight were still alive when it crashed .
#Text=After a cabin decompression occurred onboard a Learjet carrying golf pro Payne Stewart in 1999 , all the travelers lost consciousness and the plane eventually crashed with no survivors .
#Text=Passengers
#Text=Helios Airlines was unable to supply a complete passenger list , having only first initials and surnames available for investigators .

#Text=The official passenger list released by Cyprus Police , as reported by CNA , indicates that there were 22 young persons onboard aged 4-16. Most of the passengers were Cypriot , a small number were Greek and one of the pilots was German .
#Text=There were 4 Armenian passengers who lived in Cyprus .
#Text=The complete list , in Greek , has been published by the Cyprus News Agency .
#Text=Post-crash events
#Text=After the crash , a fire started around the airliner .
#Text=It was extinguished by firefighters after 2 hours .
#Text=The fire burned most of the bodies that are now being collected by special firefighter units and transferred to the city of Shisto , near Athens .
#Text=Meanwhile , the two F-16 pilots were transferred to Ministry of Defense to give their report .
#Text=The flight data recorder has been recovered .
#Text=The cockpit voice recorder was found the following morning in bad condition .
#Text=The two devices will be sent to Paris for examination .
#Text=Nektarios-Sotirios Voutas reported that a passenger ( his cousin ) sent a text message that read : " The pilot has turned blue [ in the face ] . [ F]arewell we 're freezing " .
#Text=He was arrested the following day as it appeared to be a hoax .
#Text=Reactions from Helios Airways
#Text=Helios has informed the relatives of the victims ; however , the company has been met with criticism for failing to release the passenger list quickly .
#Text=Helios Airways released a statement on their website today , stating , " Our thoughts are with the families of those on board at this difficult time . "
#Text=An emergency telephone number in Nicosia , Cyprus can be contacted at +357/70003737 , 22 – 446146 .
#Text=Official reactions
#Text=The Cypriot government has declared three days of national mourning and ordered flags to be lowered on half-mast .
#Text=Upon allegations brought by the Communications and Works Minister and the chief of police , warrants were issued by the attorney general to search Helios Airways offices
#Text=Timeline
#Text=Scheduled departure time .
#Text=09:07 ( 06:07 UTC ) Airplane takes off from Larnaka airport .
#Text=10:30 ( 07:30 UTC ) Flight fails to establish contact with the Eleftherios Venizelos Airport
#Text=Last contact with Larnaka airport reporting problem .
#Text=10:45 ( 07:45 UTC ) Scheduled arrival time in Athens .
#Text=The Hellenic Armed Forces Joint Chief of Staff , Admiral Panagiotis Chinofotis orders military planes to establish visual contact with the aircraft .
#Text=Two F-16 fighter planes take off from Néa Anghialos Air Base , Greece .
#Text=Fighter pilots note co-pilot slumped over the aircraft 's instrument panel .
#Text=Aircraft crashes near Grammatiko .
#Text=Scheduled arrival time in Prague .
#Text=Cyprus and Greece are UTC+3 , Czech Republic is UTC+2 .
#Text=About Helios Airways
#Text=Helios Airways was founded in 1999 as Cyprus ' first private airline .
#Text=It is now a subsidiary of Libra Holidays Group of Limassol , Cyprus and is registered in Cyprus .
#Text=Helios ' remaining fleet consists of 2 Boeing 737 -800 jets and an Airbus A319 .
#Text=Helios offers flights between Cyprus and London , Athens , Sofia , Warsaw , Dublin and Strasbourg .
